---
import ConditionPage from '../../components/ConditionPage.astro';
---
<ConditionPage
	title="Treatment in Clapham"
	highlight="Ankle Pain"
	heroSubtitle="Most ankle pain will heal spontaneously over a short space of time, if yours hasn't, you must come and see us."
	breadcrumb="Ankle Pain"
	seoTitle="Ankle Pain Treatment Clapham | Physiotherapy & Rehab London"
	seoDescription="Ankle pain treatment in Clapham to restore strength, stability, and movement. Expert physiotherapy for sprains, instability, and long-term recovery."
	introImage="/condition/ankle-pain/soccer-ball-boot.jpg"
	whoImage="/condition/ankle-pain/senior-hiker-shoe.jpg"
	intro={[
		"We address why your ankle pain has developed and work to restore strength, stability and confidence through targeted rehabilitation, so you can get moving well again and reduce the risk of it happening again.",
	]}
	symptomsHeading="When to get your ankle"
	symptomsHighlight="checked"
	symptomsList={[
		"Weakness in standing and squats",
		"Frequent \"going over\" or rolling of ankles",
		"Pain after rolling or twisting",
		"Ongoing swelling around the joint",
		"Instability or sensation of the ankle \"giving way\"",
		"Pain at the back of the ankle or Achilles",
		"Stiffness or difficulty moving the ankle",
		"Catching, locking, or sharp pain in the joint",
	]}
	treatmentHeading="How we treat"
	treatmentHighlight="ankle pain"
	treatmentIntro="We combine hands-on treatment with rehabilitation, which may include:"
	treatmentList={[
		"Physiotherapy to improve mobility and control",
		"Strength and rehab exercises tailored to the ankle",
		"Balance and stability training to reduce re-injury risk",
		"Gait analysis to assess walking or running patterns",
		"Advice on return to sport and activity",
	]}
	whoHeading="Who we"
	whoHighlight="help"
	whoList={[
		"People with recurring ankle instability",
		"Athletes and sports individuals recovering from sprains",
		"Runners managing Achilles or overload injuries",
		"Post-surgery rehabilitation patients",
		"Seniors looking to improve balance and reduce fall risk",
	]}
	faqs={[
		{ q: "How do I know if it's sprained or broken?", a: "97% of ankle fractures cannot take any more than 2 or 3 steps. If you can't put weight on it or have significant tenderness over the bone following a trauma, it's worth getting it checked." },
		{ q: "Why does my ankle keep giving way?", a: "Often due to reduced balance and control after a previous injury. The proprioceptive component is frequently missed in rehab, we prioritise restoring it." },
		{ q: "Can I still train with an ankle injury?", a: "In many cases, yes, with the right modifications. We'll guide you safely." },
		{ q: "Should I wear a brace?", a: "Short-term bracing may help, but the long-term focus is on building strength and stability." },
		{ q: "How long does recovery take?", a: "Minor sprains may settle in weeks; full rehabilitation duration depends on severity." },
	]}
/>
